        Hero illustration — generated separately, see prompt below.
    </figcaption>
</figure>

<section class="my-5">
    <h2 class="mb-3">What it is</h2>
    <p>
        <b>egoPdf</b> is a .NET PDF generation library that started as
        an automated port of <a href="https://www.fpdf.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FPDF</a>
        and grew into a small ecosystem:
    </p>
    <div class="row g-3">
        <div class="col-md-4">
            <div class="border rounded p-3 h-100">
                <h5 class="mb-1">
                    <a href="https://www.nuget.org/packages/EgoPDF.Generator/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">EgoPDF.Generator</a>
                </h5>
                <p class="text-muted small mb-2">Core PDF engine. MIT. SkiaSharp for font metrics + image decode.</p>
                <p class="mb-0 small">Cell / MultiCell / Image / Rect / Line / Link &mdash; plus
                    the new <code>Row</code> / <code>Stack</code> / <code>Panel</code> layout primitives,
                    <code>PushState</code> / <code>PushPos</code> scope helpers and <code>CellMeasure</code>
                    for auto-grow rows.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4">
            <div class="border rounded p-3 h-100">
                <h5 class="mb-1">
                    <a href="https://www.nuget.org/packages/EgoPDF.Barcodes/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">EgoPDF.Barcodes</a>
                </h5>
                <p class="text-muted small mb-2">1D + 2D symbologies via ZXing.Net, plus a ZPL II emulator.</p>
                <p class="mb-0 small">QR, Data Matrix, PDF417, Aztec, Code 128, Code 39, EAN, UPC, MSI,
                    Codabar, Interleaved 2 of 5 &mdash; same API surface, table-driven dispatch internally.
                    Bonus: parse ZPL II strings and render the labels as PDFs.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4">
            <div class="border rounded p-3 h-100">
                <h5 class="mb-1">
                    <a href="https://www.nuget.org/packages/EgoPDF.Markdown/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">EgoPDF.Markdown</a>
                </h5>
                <p class="text-muted small mb-2">CommonMark + GFM via Markdig, rendered through the core engine.</p>
                <p class="mb-0 small">Headings, lists, code blocks, links, autolinks, block quotes, images.
                    Built-in shortcode extension: <code>[[name k=v]]</code> blocks dispatch to handlers, so
                    Markdown can drop straight into native egoPdf primitives.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="my-5">
    <h2 class="mb-3">What changed (the agent-friendly turn)</h2>
    <p>
        The classic FPDF API is a stateful machine: every <code>Cell</code>,
        <code>SetFont</code> and <code>SetXY</code> mutates global state and
        you keep that state in your head as you write. That works for a human
        with a ruler, less well for an agent assembling a page from generic
        instructions. The recent iteration adds the missing primitives:
    </p>
    <dl class="row mt-4">
        <dt class="col-sm-3">Layout primitives</dt>
        <dd class="col-sm-9">
            <code>Row(bounds, n)</code>, <code>Stack(bounds, weights)</code>,
            <code>Panel(bounds, title, body)</code> and the <code>Rect</code>
            value type with <code>Inset</code> / <code>WithTopOffset</code> /
            <code>Right</code> / <code>Bottom</code> helpers. The math of
            <code>x + width + gap</code> disappears; the call site reads as the
            layout it produces.
        </dd>
        <dt class="col-sm-3">Scope helpers</dt>
        <dd class="col-sm-9">
            <code>using (pdf.PushState())</code> snapshots font, text, fill and
            draw colours plus line width and restores them on dispose.
            <code>using (pdf.PushPos())</code> does the same for the cursor.
            Sub-renderers compose without leaking state.
        </dd>
        <dt class="col-sm-3">Styling as data</dt>
        <dd class="col-sm-9">
            <code>PanelStyle</code> captures a frame + title look as a record
            you can reuse across calls. The PV report's <code>BrandPanel</code>
            is declared once and applied to every technical panel.
        </dd>
        <dt class="col-sm-3">Brand kit</dt>
        <dd class="col-sm-9">
            <code>EgoPdfBrand</code> centralises the colour palette, the thin
            Poppins wordmark and the <code>LoadPoppins</code> font registration
            used by Sample8 / Sample9 / SamplePhotovoltaic / SampleMarkdown's
            header band.
        </dd>
        <dt class="col-sm-3">Markdown escape hatches</dt>
        <dd class="col-sm-9">
            Block shortcodes (<code>[[barcode]]</code>, <code>[[cta]]</code>,
            <code>[[image]]</code>, <code>[[imagepair]]</code>) drop out of
            Markdown into native egoPdf code (Row, Image, brand styling) and
            back. Useful while GFM tables aren't implemented yet.
        </dd>
        <dt class="col-sm-3">Visual regression</dt>
        <dd class="col-sm-9">
            Every sample PDF is hashed on each test run and compared against
            a SHA-256 baseline. Run-to-run determinism is ensured by snapshotting
            <code>FontBuilder.Fonts</code> at module load and blanking the
            xref + <code>/CreationDate</code> in the canonical form.
        </dd>
    </dl>
</section>

