<section class="my-5">
    <h2 class="mb-3">How to use it</h2>
    <p>
        Install <code>EgoPDF.Generator</code> from NuGet, then either keep the
        classic imperative API for tight control, drop in the new primitives
        for ergonomics, or render a Markdown string and only escape to
        primitives where the visual demands it:
    </p>
<pre class="border rounded p-3 bg-light"><code>// 1. Classic imperative
using var pdf = new FPdf("invoice.pdf");
pdf.AddPage(PageSizeEnum.A4);
pdf.SetFont("Helvetica", "B", 16);
pdf.Cell(40, 10, "INVOICE", "0", 1, AlignEnum.Right);

// 2. With primitives
var cols = pdf.Row(pdf.Bounds(), new[] { 2.0, 1.0 }, gap: 3);
pdf.Panel(cols[0], "DETAILS", brandStyle, content =&gt; {
    // body lives inside `content`, state restored on return
});

// 3. Markdown
var theme = MarkdownTheme.Default;
theme.Shortcodes.Register("barcode", new BarcodeShortcode());
MarkdownRenderer.Render(pdf, markdownSource, theme);
</code></pre>
    <p>
        See <a asp-page="/Examples">Examples</a> for live PDFs of every pattern
        above, or read the
        <a href="https://github.com/marcoregueira/egopdf/blob/master/RECIPES.md"
           target="_blank" rel="noopener">RECIPES.md</a>
        catalog for copy-pasteable snippets.
    </p>
</section>

